{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8a432e120e1ad1a4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                             Bring Music The Horizon: Music-Driven 360◦\n2\t                                                          Video Generation\n3\t\n4\t                                             Kai Hsu, Tsai1 , Yong Wei, Fu1 , Hung I, Yang1 , and Yu-Chih Chen1\n5\t\n6\t                                            Department of Computer Science, National Yang Ming Chiao Tung University,\n7\t                                                                    Hsinchu 300093, Taiwan\n8\t                                          {chris.cs12, willyfu0905.cs12, holdtensec.cs12, berriechen}@nycu.edu.tw\n9\t\n10\t                                                Abstract. Music visualization offers a powerful way to enhance listen-\n11\t                                                ers’ understanding and experience of music by translating auditory sig-\n12\t                                                nals into visual forms. However, most existing approaches either rely\n13\t                                                heavily on lyrics or generate flat, non-immersive videos similar to con-\n14\t                                                ventional music videos, which limits their ability to convey the emotional\n15\t                                                dynamics of music and provide an immersive listening experience.\n16\tarXiv:2607.13471v1 [cs.CV] 15 Jul 2026\n17\t\n18\t\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t                                                We propose Bring Music The Horizon, an emotion-aware pipeline for\n22\t                                                music-driven 360◦ video generation. Given an input song, our work first\n23\t                                                estimates its emotional trajectory by predicting valence-arousal values [1]\n24\t                                                at the level of every four bars. These values are then converted into\n25\t                                                emotion-aware visual guidance using EmotiCrafter [2], and these guid-\n26\t                                                ance vectors can be manipulated by the SEGA framework [3], which\n27\t                                                provides fine-grained semantic control for keyframe generation. Finally,\n28\t                                                image-to-video models are applied to the generated keyframes to synthe-\n29\t                                                size temporally continuous 360◦ videos for immersive music visualization.\n30\t                                                Our pipeline generates 360◦ music visualization videos that reflect the\n31\t                                                emotional progression and temporal structure of the input song. We\n32\t                                                demonstrate its capability using songs from different genres and pro-\n33\t                                                vide qualitative comparisons with From-Sound-To-Sight [4], a represen-\n34\t                                                tative audio-to-visual generation baseline, on our project page at https:\n35\t                                                //etoile-et-toi-mp3.github.io/BMTH_Project_Page/.\n36\t                                                Keywords: Music Visualization · 360◦ Video Generation · Music Emo-\n37\t                                                tion Recognition · Multimodal Generation\n38\t\n39\t\n40\t                                         1    Introduction\n41\t                                         1.1 Motivation\n42\t                                         Music visualization aims to enhance how listeners perceive and experience music\n43\t                                         by translating auditory signals into visual content. However, existing approaches\n44\t                                         are often limited to fixed-view or flat videos, resembling conventional music\n45\t                                         videos rather than immersive visual experiences. Many methods also rely heavily\n46\t                                         on lyrics to infer visual semantics, which limits their applicability to instrumental\n47\t                                         music and may overlook the continuous emotional dynamics embedded in the\n48\t                                         audio itself.\n49\t                                           To address these limitations, we propose Bring Music The Horizon, a music-\n50\t                                         driven pipeline for generating immersive 360◦ videos. Our method focuses on\n51\t                                         modeling the temporal evolution of musical emotion and synthesizing 360◦ visual\n52\t                                         scenes that align with both the affective and structural progression of the song.\n53\t\f2      Tsai et al.\n54\t\n55\t1.2   Related Work\n56\tRecent music visualization methods combine music information retrieval (MIR)\n57\tand generative models to synthesize visual content from audio. However, many\n58\tapproaches rely on lyrics or other surface-level semantic cues, which may weaken\n59\tthe connection between the generated visuals and the intrinsic musical properties\n60\tsuch as rhythm, intensity, timbre, and emotional progression. Moreover, most\n61\tprior work targets narrative-style flat music videos rather than immersive 360◦\n62\tvisualization.\n63\t   Jeong et al. [5] proposed an audio-reactive video generation model that maps\n64\taudio signals to semantic and temporal visual dynamics, such as generating rain\n65\tintensity according to audio magnitude. Our work shares the broader goal of\n66\taudio-reactive visual generation, but focuses specifically on music-driven immer-\n67\tsive visualization, where both emotional trajectories and musical structure are\n68\tused to guide 360◦ video generation.\n69\t\n70\t1.3   Our Pipeline and Limitations\n71\tOur pipeline consists of three main modules. The (i) MIR module extracts mu-\n72\tsical features such as tempo, downbeat timestamps, and valence-arousal (V-A)\n73\tvalues [1] for each four-bar segment. The (ii) Emotion-guided 360◦ Keyframe\n74\tGeneration module incorporates the estimated emotional features into the vi-\n75\tsual generation process to produce affect-aligned 360◦ keyframes. The (iii) 360◦\n76\tVideo Generation module then applies image-to-video (I2V) models to gener-\n77\tate dynamic clips and transition clips, which are concatenated into the final\n78\timmersive music visualization video.\n79\t   While the proposed pipeline can generate emotion-aware and temporally struc-\n80\ttured 360◦ music visualization videos, several limitations remain. Similar V-A\n81\tvalues may produce repetitive keyframes, and visible seams can appear due to\n82\tboundary inconsistencies in generated 360◦ videos. The current output resolu-\n83\ttion is still limited, and the forward-moving visual effect cannot yet be fully\n84\tcontrolled, which may affect motion comfort. In addition, overly long prompts\n85\tmay degrade 360◦ generation and cause the model to produce flat rather than\n86\t360◦ , immersive visuals.\n87\t\n88\t2     Method\n89\tGiven an input song S and a user-specified base prompt pbase , our pipeline gen-\n90\terates an emotionally and temporally aligned 360◦ music visualization. As shown\n91\tin Fig. 1, the song is first analyzed to extract its bar-level temporal structure\n92\tand a sequence of valence-arousal (V-A) values that describe the emotional tra-\n93\tjectory of the music. These musical cues are then used to adapt the base prompt\n94\tinto emotion-aware panoramic keyframes, allowing the visual content to preserve\n95\tthe user-provided concept while evolving with the song’s emotional progression.\n96\tFinally, the generated keyframes are animated and connected in musical order\n97\tto produce a complete 360◦ video whose scene dynamics and transitions follow\n98\tthe structure of the input song.\n99\t\f             Bring Music The Horizon: Music-Driven 360◦ Video Generation                                               3\n100\t\n101\t\n102\t\n103\t\n104\tFig. 1: Overview of the proposed music-driven 360◦ visualization pipeline. Given an\n105\tinput song and a user-specified base prompt, the MIR module extracts musical struc-\n106\tture and downbeat-level timing cues, while the Dynamic V-A Regressor estimates a\n107\tsequence of valence-arousal conditions. These emotion conditions are converted into\n108\temotional residuals by EmotiCrafter [2] and used with SEGA [3] and SDXL [6] 360◦\n109\tLoRA [7] to generate emotion-aware panoramic keyframes. The keyframes are then\n110\tanimated by Wan-based image-to-video generation to produce the final 360◦ dynamic\n111\tvisualization.\n112\t\n113\t  Formally, the overall process is defined as\n114\t                         (S, p_{\\mathrm {base}}) \\rightarrow (B, U, E) \\rightarrow K \\rightarrow V_{\\mathrm {360}}    (1)\n115\t where B = {bi }N                                                            T\n116\t                    i=1 denotes the extracted downbeat timestamps, U = {ut }t=1\n117\tdenotes the resulting four-bar music units, and E = {et }Tt=1 denotes the corre-\n118\tsponding emotional trajectory. Each emotion condition is represented as et =\n119\t(vt , at ) in the V-A space. The keyframe generation stage produces a sequence of\n120\tpanoramic keyframes K = {kt }Tt=1 , and the video generation stage synthesizes\n121\tthe final 360◦ music visualization V360 .\n122\t2.1 Music Information Retrieval (MIR)\n123\tThe MIR module analyzes the input song S and extracts its temporal structure\n124\tand emotional trajectory:\n125\t                                           f_{\\mathrm {MIR}}(S) = (B, U, E).                                          (2)\n126\tWe first use All-In-One [8] to estimate downbeat timestamps B and functional\n127\tsegment information, which provide the temporal structure of the song. Based\n128\ton the extracted downbeats, we group the song into four-bar units U . For each\n129\tunit ut , our proposed Dynamic Valence-Arousal regressor predicts an emotion\n130\tcondition et = (vt , at ), where vt and at denote the valence and arousal val-\n131\tues, respectively. This regressor is trained to estimate segment-level emotional\n132\tdynamics directly from music audio, rather than relying on lyrics or manually\n133\tassigned emotion labels. The resulting V-A sequence E is used as the emotional\n134\tcondition for subsequent visual generation, enabling the generated visuals to\n135\tfollow both the musical structure and the emotional progression of the song.\n136\t2.2 Emotion-guided 360◦ Keyframe Generation\n137\tThe keyframe generation module maps each four-bar music unit to an emotion-\n138\taware panoramic keyframe:\n139\t\f4       Tsai et al.\n140\t\n141\t                                 f_{\\mathrm {key}}(p_{\\mathrm {base}}, e_t) = k_t.    (3)\n142\t\n143\t For each unit ut , the base prompt pbase and its corresponding emotion condi-\n144\ttion et are fed into a retrained EmotiCrafter model [2] to obtain an emotional\n145\tresidual rt . This residual describes how the visual semantics of the base prompt\n146\tshould be shifted toward the target emotion. We then use rt as a SEGA guid-\n147\tance condition gt [3], enabling fine-grained semantic control during the diffusion\n148\tprocess. Finally, SDXL [6] with a 360◦ LoRA adapter [7] is used to generate\n149\tthe panoramic keyframe kt . This design allows each keyframe to maintain the\n150\tuser-specified scene concept while reflecting the emotion predicted from the cor-\n151\tresponding music segment. Repeating this process for all T units yields the\n152\tkeyframe sequence K = {kt }Tt=1 .\n153\t\n154\t2.3   360◦ Video Generation\n155\tThe video generation module transforms the keyframe sequence K into the final\n156\timmersive visualization:\n157\t                                f_{\\mathrm {video}}(K) = V_{\\mathrm {360}}.  (4)\n158\tEach keyframe kt anchors one four-bar video unit. The first three bars are syn-\n159\tthesized as a dynamic scene dt using Wan-I2V [9]. The final bar is generated\n160\tas a transition clip ρt using Wan-flf2v [9], which connects the current dynamic\n161\tscene to the next keyframe kt+1 . By concatenating all dynamic scenes {dt }Tt=1\n162\tand transition clips {ρt }Tt=1 in temporal order, the module produces a complete\n163\t360◦ music visualization video V360 , in which scene changes are aligned with the\n164\ttemporal structure and emotional flow of the input song.\n165\t\n166\t3     Results and Conclusion\n167\tThe experimental results show that the proposed pipeline can generate 360◦\n168\tmusic visualization videos that are directly viewable in VR headsets. The gen-\n169\terated scenes follow the temporal structure of the input songs, while the visual\n170\tatmosphere and scene transitions reflect the estimated emotional trajectory at\n171\tdifferent musical segments. These results demonstrate the potential of extending\n172\tconventional music visualization from flat videos to immersive VR experiences.\n173\t   Overall, this work presents an emotion-aware and structure-aligned pipeline\n174\tfor music-driven 360◦ video generation. By integrating dynamic music emotion\n175\tprediction, emotion-guided keyframe generation, and 360◦ image-to-video syn-\n176\tthesis, the proposed method provides a practical framework for immersive music\n177\tvisualization. In addition, retraining EmotiCrafter with a custom dataset helps\n178\treduce undesired human-activity artifacts from the original model, resulting in\n179\tcleaner and more scene-focused visual outputs. We believe this work establishes a\n180\tpromising foundation for future research on cross-modal and immersive content\n181\tcreation.\n182\tAcknowledgements. This work was supported by the MOE Yushan Young Scholar\n183\tProgram under Grant MOE-114-YSFEE-0010-008-P1 and NSTC Taiwan under\n184\tGrant NSTC 115-2813-C-A49-161-E.\n185\t\f              Bring Music The Horizon: Music-Driven 360◦ Video Generation             5\n186\t\n187\tReferences\n188\t1. Russell, J.: A circumplex model of affect. Journal of Personality and Social Psychol-\n189\t   ogy 39, 1161–1178 (12 1980). https://doi.org/10.1037/h0077714\n190\t2. Dang, S., He, Y., Ling, L., Qian, Z., Zhao, N., Cao, N.: Emoticrafter: Text-to-\n191\t   emotional-image generation based on valence-arousal model. In: Proceedings of the\n192\t   IEEE/CVF International Conference on Computer Vision. pp. 15218–15228 (2025)\n193\t3. Brack, M., Friedrich, F., Hintersdorf, D., Struppek, L., Schramowski, P., Kersting,\n194\t   K.: Sega: Instructing text-to-image models using semantic guidance (2023), https:\n195\t   //arxiv.org/abs/2301.12247\n196\t4. Vitasovic, L., Graßhof, S., Kloft, A.M., Lehtola, V.V., Cunneen, M., Starostka, J.,\n197\t   McGarry, G., Li, K., Brandt, S.S.: From sound to sight: Towards ai-authored music\n198\t   videos (2025), https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.00029\n199\t5. Jeong, Y., Ryoo, W., Lee, S., Seo, D., Byeon, W., Kim, S., Kim, J.: The power of\n200\t   sound (tpos): Audio reactive video generation with stable diffusion. In: Proceedings\n201\t   of the IEEE/CVF International Conference on Computer Vision. pp. 7822–7832\n202\t   (2023)\n203\t6. Podell, D., English, Z., Lacey, K., Blattmann, A., Dockhorn, T., Müller, J., Penna,\n204\t   J., Rombach, R.: Sdxl: Improving latent diffusion models for high-resolution image\n205\t   synthesis (2023), https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.01952\n206\t7. artificialguybr: 360Redmond: 360 degree panorama LoRA for SDXL. https://\n207\t   huggingface.co/artificialguybr/360Redmond (2024)\n208\t8. Kim, T., Nam, J.: All-in-one metrical and functional structure analysis with neigh-\n209\t   borhood attentions on demixed audio. In: IEEE Workshop on Applications of Signal\n210\t   Processing to Audio and Acoustics (WASPAA) (2023)\n211\t9. Wan, T., Wang, A., Ai, B., Wen, B., Mao, C., Xie, C.W., Chen, D., Yu, F., Zhao,\n212\t   H., Yang, J., Zeng, J., Wang, J., Zhang, J., Zhou, J., Wang, J., Chen, J., Zhu, K.,\n213\t   Zhao, K., Yan, K., Huang, L., Feng, M., Zhang, N., Li, P., Wu, P., Chu, R., Feng,\n214\t   R., Zhang, S., Sun, S., Fang, T., Wang, T., Gui, T., Weng, T., Shen, T., Lin, W.,\n215\t   Wang, W., Wang, W., Zhou, W., Wang, W., Shen, W., Yu, W., Shi, X., Huang, X.,\n216\t   Xu, X., Kou, Y., Lv, Y., Li, Y., Liu, Y., Wang, Y., Zhang, Y., Huang, Y., Li, Y.,\n217\t   Wu, Y., Liu, Y., Pan, Y., Zheng, Y., Hong, Y., Shi, Y., Feng, Y., Jiang, Z., Han,\n218\t   Z., Wu, Z.F., Liu, Z.: Wan: Open and advanced large-scale video generative models\n219\t   (2025), https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.20314\n220\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "840221e4-aed3-4368-b973-2460b79f0cd1", "uuid": "f47161b1-ef5f-4551-9ab8-b4453d86dbe7", "timestamp": "2026-07-16T05:53:57.511Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/bmth_2607.13471v1.txt", "content": "                                             Bring Music The Horizon: Music-Driven 360◦\n                                                          Video Generation\n\n                                             Kai Hsu, Tsai1 , Yong Wei, Fu1 , Hung I, Yang1 , and Yu-Chih Chen1\n\n                                            Department of Computer Science, National Yang Ming Chiao Tung University,\n                                                                    Hsinchu 300093, Taiwan\n                                          {chris.cs12, willyfu0905.cs12, holdtensec.cs12, berriechen}@nycu.edu.tw\n\n                                                Abstract. Music visualization offers a powerful way to enhance listen-\n                                                ers’ understanding and experience of music by translating auditory sig-\n                                                nals into visual forms. However, most existing approaches either rely\n                                                heavily on lyrics or generate flat, non-immersive videos similar to con-\n                                                ventional music videos, which limits their ability to convey the emotional\n                                                dynamics of music and provide an immersive listening experience.\narXiv:2607.13471v1 [cs.CV] 15 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                                We propose Bring Music The Horizon, an emotion-aware pipeline for\n                                                music-driven 360◦ video generation. Given an input song, our work first\n                                                estimates its emotional trajectory by predicting valence-arousal values [1]\n                                                at the level of every four bars. These values are then converted into\n                                                emotion-aware visual guidance using EmotiCrafter [2], and these guid-\n                                                ance vectors can be manipulated by the SEGA framework [3], which\n                                                provides fine-grained semantic control for keyframe generation. Finally,\n                                                image-to-video models are applied to the generated keyframes to synthe-\n                                                size temporally continuous 360◦ videos for immersive music visualization.\n                                                Our pipeline generates 360◦ music visualization videos that reflect the\n                                                emotional progression and temporal structure of the input song. We\n                                                demonstrate its capability using songs from different genres and pro-\n                                                vide qualitative comparisons with From-Sound-To-Sight [4], a represen-\n                                                tative audio-to-visual generation baseline, on our project page at https:\n                                                //etoile-et-toi-mp3.github.io/BMTH_Project_Page/.\n                                                Keywords: Music Visualization · 360◦ Video Generation · Music Emo-\n                                                tion Recognition · Multimodal Generation\n\n\n                                         1    Introduction\n                                         1.1 Motivation\n                                         Music visualization aims to enhance how listeners perceive and experience music\n                                         by translating auditory signals into visual content. However, existing approaches\n                                         are often limited to fixed-view or flat videos, resembling conventional music\n                                         videos rather than immersive visual experiences. Many methods also rely heavily\n                                         on lyrics to infer visual semantics, which limits their applicability to instrumental\n                                         music and may overlook the continuous emotional dynamics embedded in the\n                                         audio itself.\n                                           To address these limitations, we propose Bring Music The Horizon, a music-\n                                         driven pipeline for generating immersive 360◦ videos. Our method focuses on\n                                         modeling the temporal evolution of musical emotion and synthesizing 360◦ visual\n                                         scenes that align with both the affective and structural progression of the song.\n\f2      Tsai et al.\n\n1.2   Related Work\nRecent music visualization methods combine music information retrieval (MIR)\nand generative models to synthesize visual content from audio. However, many\napproaches rely on lyrics or other surface-level semantic cues, which may weaken\nthe connection between the generated visuals and the intrinsic musical properties\nsuch as rhythm, intensity, timbre, and emotional progression. Moreover, most\nprior work targets narrative-style flat music videos rather than immersive 360◦\nvisualization.\n   Jeong et al. [5] proposed an audio-reactive video generation model that maps\naudio signals to semantic and temporal visual dynamics, such as generating rain\nintensity according to audio magnitude. Our work shares the broader goal of\naudio-reactive visual generation, but focuses specifically on music-driven immer-\nsive visualization, where both emotional trajectories and musical structure are\nused to guide 360◦ video generation.\n\n1.3   Our Pipeline and Limitations\nOur pipeline consists of three main modules. The (i) MIR module extracts mu-\nsical features such as tempo, downbeat timestamps, and valence-arousal (V-A)\nvalues [1] for each four-bar segment. The (ii) Emotion-guided 360◦ Keyframe\nGeneration module incorporates the estimated emotional features into the vi-\nsual generation process to produce affect-aligned 360◦ keyframes. The (iii) 360◦\nVideo Generation module then applies image-to-video (I2V) models to gener-\nate dynamic clips and transition clips, which are concatenated into the final\nimmersive music visualization video.\n   While the proposed pipeline can generate emotion-aware and temporally struc-\ntured 360◦ music visualization videos, several limitations remain. Similar V-A\nvalues may produce repetitive keyframes, and visible seams can appear due to\nboundary inconsistencies in generated 360◦ videos. The current output resolu-\ntion is still limited, and the forward-moving visual effect cannot yet be fully\ncontrolled, which may affect motion comfort. In addition, overly long prompts\nmay degrade 360◦ generation and cause the model to produce flat rather than\n360◦ , immersive visuals.\n\n2     Method\nGiven an input song S and a user-specified base prompt pbase , our pipeline gen-\nerates an emotionally and temporally aligned 360◦ music visualization. As shown\nin Fig. 1, the song is first analyzed to extract its bar-level temporal structure\nand a sequence of valence-arousal (V-A) values that describe the emotional tra-\njectory of the music. These musical cues are then used to adapt the base prompt\ninto emotion-aware panoramic keyframes, allowing the visual content to preserve\nthe user-provided concept while evolving with the song’s emotional progression.\nFinally, the generated keyframes are animated and connected in musical order\nto produce a complete 360◦ video whose scene dynamics and transitions follow\nthe structure of the input song.\n\f             Bring Music The Horizon: Music-Driven 360◦ Video Generation                                               3\n\n\n\n\nFig. 1: Overview of the proposed music-driven 360◦ visualization pipeline. Given an\ninput song and a user-specified base prompt, the MIR module extracts musical struc-\nture and downbeat-level timing cues, while the Dynamic V-A Regressor estimates a\nsequence of valence-arousal conditions. These emotion conditions are converted into\nemotional residuals by EmotiCrafter [2] and used with SEGA [3] and SDXL [6] 360◦\nLoRA [7] to generate emotion-aware panoramic keyframes. The keyframes are then\nanimated by Wan-based image-to-video generation to produce the final 360◦ dynamic\nvisualization.\n\n  Formally, the overall process is defined as\n                         (S, p_{\\mathrm {base}}) \\rightarrow (B, U, E) \\rightarrow K \\rightarrow V_{\\mathrm {360}}    (1)\n where B = {bi }N                                                            T\n                    i=1 denotes the extracted downbeat timestamps, U = {ut }t=1\ndenotes the resulting four-bar music units, and E = {et }Tt=1 denotes the corre-\nsponding emotional trajectory. Each emotion condition is represented as et =\n(vt , at ) in the V-A space. The keyframe generation stage produces a sequence of\npanoramic keyframes K = {kt }Tt=1 , and the video generation stage synthesizes\nthe final 360◦ music visualization V360 .\n2.1 Music Information Retrieval (MIR)\nThe MIR module analyzes the input song S and extracts its temporal structure\nand emotional trajectory:\n                                           f_{\\mathrm {MIR}}(S) = (B, U, E).                                          (2)\nWe first use All-In-One [8] to estimate downbeat timestamps B and functional\nsegment information, which provide the temporal structure of the song. Based\non the extracted downbeats, we group the song into four-bar units U . For each\nunit ut , our proposed Dynamic Valence-Arousal regressor predicts an emotion\ncondition et = (vt , at ), where vt and at denote the valence and arousal val-\nues, respectively. This regressor is trained to estimate segment-level emotional\ndynamics directly from music audio, rather than relying on lyrics or manually\nassigned emotion labels. The resulting V-A sequence E is used as the emotional\ncondition for subsequent visual generation, enabling the generated visuals to\nfollow both the musical structure and the emotional progression of the song.\n2.2 Emotion-guided 360◦ Keyframe Generation\nThe keyframe generation module maps each four-bar music unit to an emotion-\naware panoramic keyframe:\n\f4       Tsai et al.\n\n                                 f_{\\mathrm {key}}(p_{\\mathrm {base}}, e_t) = k_t.    (3)\n\n For each unit ut , the base prompt pbase and its corresponding emotion condi-\ntion et are fed into a retrained EmotiCrafter model [2] to obtain an emotional\nresidual rt . This residual describes how the visual semantics of the base prompt\nshould be shifted toward the target emotion. We then use rt as a SEGA guid-\nance condition gt [3], enabling fine-grained semantic control during the diffusion\nprocess. Finally, SDXL [6] with a 360◦ LoRA adapter [7] is used to generate\nthe panoramic keyframe kt . This design allows each keyframe to maintain the\nuser-specified scene concept while reflecting the emotion predicted from the cor-\nresponding music segment. Repeating this process for all T units yields the\nkeyframe sequence K = {kt }Tt=1 .\n\n2.3   360◦ Video Generation\nThe video generation module transforms the keyframe sequence K into the final\nimmersive visualization:\n                                f_{\\mathrm {video}}(K) = V_{\\mathrm {360}}.  (4)\nEach keyframe kt anchors one four-bar video unit. The first three bars are syn-\nthesized as a dynamic scene dt using Wan-I2V [9]. The final bar is generated\nas a transition clip ρt using Wan-flf2v [9], which connects the current dynamic\nscene to the next keyframe kt+1 . By concatenating all dynamic scenes {dt }Tt=1\nand transition clips {ρt }Tt=1 in temporal order, the module produces a complete\n360◦ music visualization video V360 , in which scene changes are aligned with the\ntemporal structure and emotional flow of the input song.\n\n3     Results and Conclusion\nThe experimental results show that the proposed pipeline can generate 360◦\nmusic visualization videos that are directly viewable in VR headsets. The gen-\nerated scenes follow the temporal structure of the input songs, while the visual\natmosphere and scene transitions reflect the estimated emotional trajectory at\ndifferent musical segments. These results demonstrate the potential of extending\nconventional music visualization from flat videos to immersive VR experiences.\n   Overall, this work presents an emotion-aware and structure-aligned pipeline\nfor music-driven 360◦ video generation. By integrating dynamic music emotion\nprediction, emotion-guided keyframe generation, and 360◦ image-to-video syn-\nthesis, the proposed method provides a practical framework for immersive music\nvisualization. In addition, retraining EmotiCrafter with a custom dataset helps\nreduce undesired human-activity artifacts from the original model, resulting in\ncleaner and more scene-focused visual outputs. We believe this work establishes a\npromising foundation for future research on cross-modal and immersive content\ncreation.\nAcknowledgements. This work was supported by the MOE Yushan Young Scholar\nProgram under Grant MOE-114-YSFEE-0010-008-P1 and NSTC Taiwan under\nGrant NSTC 115-2813-C-A49-161-E.\n\f              Bring Music The Horizon: Music-Driven 360◦ Video Generation             5\n\nReferences\n1. Russell, J.: A circumplex model of affect. Journal of Personality and Social Psychol-\n   ogy 39, 1161–1178 (12 1980). https://doi.org/10.1037/h0077714\n2. Dang, S., He, Y., Ling, L., Qian, Z., Zhao, N., Cao, N.: Emoticrafter: Text-to-\n   emotional-image generation based on valence-arousal model. In: Proceedings of the\n   IEEE/CVF International Conference on Computer Vision. pp. 15218–15228 (2025)\n3. Brack, M., Friedrich, F., Hintersdorf, D., Struppek, L., Schramowski, P., Kersting,\n   K.: Sega: Instructing text-to-image models using semantic guidance (2023), https:\n   //arxiv.org/abs/2301.12247\n4. Vitasovic, L., Graßhof, S., Kloft, A.M., Lehtola, V.V., Cunneen, M., Starostka, J.,\n   McGarry, G., Li, K., Brandt, S.S.: From sound to sight: Towards ai-authored music\n   videos (2025), https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.00029\n5. Jeong, Y., Ryoo, W., Lee, S., Seo, D., Byeon, W., Kim, S., Kim, J.: The power of\n   sound (tpos): Audio reactive video generation with stable diffusion. In: Proceedings\n   of the IEEE/CVF International Conference on Computer Vision. pp. 7822–7832\n   (2023)\n6. Podell, D., English, Z., Lacey, K., Blattmann, A., Dockhorn, T., Müller, J., Penna,\n   J., Rombach, R.: Sdxl: Improving latent diffusion models for high-resolution image\n   synthesis (2023), https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.01952\n7. artificialguybr: 360Redmond: 360 degree panorama LoRA for SDXL. https://\n   huggingface.co/artificialguybr/360Redmond (2024)\n8. Kim, T., Nam, J.: All-in-one metrical and functional structure analysis with neigh-\n   borhood attentions on demixed audio. In: IEEE Workshop on Applications of Signal\n   Processing to Audio and Acoustics (WASPAA) (2023)\n9. Wan, T., Wang, A., Ai, B., Wen, B., Mao, C., Xie, C.W., Chen, D., Yu, F., Zhao,\n   H., Yang, J., Zeng, J., Wang, J., Zhang, J., Zhou, J., Wang, J., Chen, J., Zhu, K.,\n   Zhao, K., Yan, K., Huang, L., Feng, M., Zhang, N., Li, P., Wu, P., Chu, R., Feng,\n   R., Zhang, S., Sun, S., Fang, T., Wang, T., Gui, T., Weng, T., Shen, T., Lin, W.,\n   Wang, W., Wang, W., Zhou, W., Wang, W., Shen, W., Yu, W., Shi, X., Huang, X.,\n   Xu, X., Kou, Y., Lv, Y., Li, Y., Liu, Y., Wang, Y., Zhang, Y., Huang, Y., Li, Y.,\n   Wu, Y., Liu, Y., Pan, Y., Zheng, Y., Hong, Y., Shi, Y., Feng, Y., Jiang, Z., Han,\n   Z., Wu, Z.F., Liu, Z.: Wan: Open and advanced large-scale video generative models\n   (2025), https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.20314\n\f", "numLines": 220, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 220}}}
